segments.text: Okay, you're describing the program at the... Now, we would have cabins, we called it.
And in each cabin, we would have quartered about 10 students.
And a volunteer from civil engineering would... A student would...
be in the cabin and sort of look after the kids and tell them to knock it off or get the lights out and this sort of thing.
It was kind of GI at first.
I gradually got worked out of that, but we would blow the bugle calls in this.
By the time we got in about 1955, we didn't do that.
The civil engineers had a classroom.
Those that didn't want to volunteer would live in cabins off to themselves.
The geology students, I put them up at the far end.
because they had very little, they had no places that is formed.
We had good food, we had cabins back out behind the dining hall for the cooks, and it was pleasant duty for everybody.
I had no difficulty recruiting fine professors.
Now, normally about, what was the total enrollment per six weeks?
Oh, we were limited to about 250 students total.
Did you normally fill up?
Oh, yes.
So 500 per summer.
Now, that didn't include the CEs and the geography.
Oh, I forgot those.
I was going to ask about what percentage of the entering freshman class would go to Junction?
I'm a little bit hesitant here because, frankly, I don't remember too accurately.
But I'll tell you a source for that.
McCandless...
The first thing he did when he got to be assistant dean, he sent a graduate student over and said, now, Austin, are you going to write that dissertation on the adjunct, or are you not?
And I said, well, Haskell, Wayne Hall helped me.
He said, Austin, you have a job at this university all your life.
You don't worry about it.
Somewhere on this campus, you're going to be used.
But he said, you're going to pay a penalty.
I said, yes, sir, I understand that.
I was very content because Haskell, I found a chance to do in life what I really wanted to do.
What could be better?
I am so grateful.
As you look back on the adjunct,

Did you feel that the youngsters that went there demonstrated, once they got to the main campus as full-time students, they demonstrated that they'd been, that those were... Oh, mechanics found that they had done markedly better, markedly better.
And it kind of was one of these things that worked itself out.
In a few summers, say beginning about 55,
The better students you see would apply and get a reservation before, they always do, you know, that's one reason they're what they are.
So this was not, by and large, after it got going, these were not the marginal.
Oh no, no, these were the best students.
Well, Jeff Wentworth, I knew that his father, his father and I worked in the library together.
it was kind of typical of that and you you every once in a while you will hear someone say I was at the adjunct surely you have some anecdotes you can share about some experiences well yes
I think, though, that I would like to think about that and jot some things down.
But we did not have a discipline talk.
Haskell, we, Louie Howe used to say, Austin, you going to excuse me from the back of large service tonight?
And I'd say, no, Louie, we wouldn't want to miss you.
But I simply had a meeting the first night of everyone.
And I told them there are two purposes at coming out here at Six Feet.
One purpose is to learn.
The other purpose is to teach.
There are no privileges other than the privilege to learn and the privilege to teach.
And I don't want to see any sign of privileges.
One nut, one summer, stomped some Coke bottles on the ground.
I made him dig them out and wash them.
We had an old history talk.
One little anecdote I remember that Louie Howard told that they took, in his English class, they took a break to go, I think, go get a Coke or something in the middle of the morning.
And as they're walking over there, one of the kids almost stabbed his foot on a horse crippler cactus.
When they got back,
Louis a sign they were doing in their English class.
He said, all right, I want one of you, I want each of you to write me a one-page essay on something that you have learned or discovered in the last two or three days.
This youngster wrote his essay about having discovered a new kind of cactus, and this young man's ear had heard Louis say the word as W-H-O-R-E-S, crippler.
And
Louis said that the facial expression of the youngster when he gave him the paperback was demonstration that it was not a prank, that he had misunderstood the word.
Let's see, I'm assuming that few of them, if any, had cars, so that you didn't worry about their driving around or anything?
Dr. Segrist took care of that.
We gave them, they had to register their car with us.
But I'm sure they didn't wander around much.
Oh no, oh no.
That car had to be back in on the campus in the place assigned them at 10 o'clock.
As far as you know, was that a self-supporting?
that is, it paid?
Well, yes.
I know this, that we became pretty crowded there after about 1959.
Dean Graham was the one that worked this out.
What they did was they borrowed from the red dollar the money that was needed and they built some additional, well they built a faculty house and they did some other things.
The facilities were pretty good.
They, the,
The geology students were a little bit of a problem.
That was because I think that they didn't have formal classes.
And they were upperclassmen.
They were upperclassmen.
And you had to do, every once in a while, you had to do something pretty abrupt to kind of remind them.
We told them very clearly that they were not to take those cars out on the grass
to one of the cabins to put their gear in.
The grass is too precious to me.
Well, the geology, two cars of geology, they paid no attention.
And so when they, I waited until the evening meal and then I asked them to come by and see me.
I told them I would need their keys.
And they said, what do you mean?
I said, I mean that I'm going to ground you.
And furthermore, I'm not only going to ground you, but I'm going to take your permission to keep the car on the campus.
I said, now, if you want to park it up there on that road that runs into it,
That's up to you, but you're not going to bring it on us.
And oh man, they began to try every trick in the world.
Well, I thought it over that night, and I told them the next morning that I think I'd just make that probation.
And so I had to kind of do that.
The geologists were kind of free spirits.
And I've learned over the years, and I mean this in a kind way, but geologists, they like this he-man image, you know, tough.
Now surely there must be a student prank or two that you can remember.
that can be put on tape?
Oh yes, I can help that.
What was that song they were all singing that summer?
It was a song that, well, it was a popular song.
So we had a speaker system with the speakers up above the dining hall typical thing and we would blow taps and that was just an easy way to say get your lights out.
So one night about three o'clock in the morning
This burst of music sounded.
Just tremendous sound.
And it was playing this song.
And there was a young man named Clay.
He was the camp counselor and he was on the...
staff of the basic division.
But he needed extra money and he tore out for the dining hall.
He couldn't get in.
And the music was just, oh man, you could hear it in junctions.
Calls were being, I got telephone calls and we
Well, we didn't know what in the dickens we were going to do.
And one of the fellas said, I bet you can get through the bathroom window.
And we said, oh, well, there's just a women's bath, a restroom.
And I said, well, get in the window anyway, if you can get inside.
So we got one of the little skinny ones, and we got him in, and he got in there and turned it off.
Did you ever discover who the culprit was?
Well, you know, Haskell, sometimes it's better to just let someone know.
What is it the blacks say?
Leave it be.
Leave it be.
Yes, it was something everyone talked about, but they shot their wad because we certainly took care of that outlet.
And by and large, was there a good grade performance rate by Junction students in the courses they took out there?
Yes.
We rarely ever, frankly, had a student fail.
I'm going to make an L. Who were some of the faculty members that you remember out there with greatest pride and joy?
Well, you know, I had good men.
I had good men.
In the English department, I had people like Mr. Louis Howe.
I had Mr. Criswell, the kids call him Mama.
We had Stanley Archer that died recently.
We had, oh,
Well, in math, we had Hale Perry, who probably was one of the best supervisors of introductory math.
Bill Perry was his understudy.
Perry will tell you that Hale was something else.
We had a Mr. Liles, an old-fashioned schoolteacher type.
We had this fella from Alabama.
The kids called him Deacon.
I have to think about this.
We had excellent people, with an exception or two.
And you didn't have any trouble recruiting faculty?
Oh, no.
Back in the 50s, or even 60s, summer work was... Oh, sure.
That's right.
That was a bonus.
Oh, yeah.
That's right.
And I remember with Louie Howe, people like him went fairly regularly.
We wouldn't open without Louie.
About how many faculty would you have per six weeks' term?
Oh, we would have three in English and three in history.
Wait, you said history?
Yes.
Uh-huh.
Yeah, pre-
Oh, that's right.
Treat.
Treat was quite good.
I remember one summer, Treat would hold a help session after evening meal.
And the kids would get him started.
And he's like all of us.
If you get in your discipline, you get started.
But they'd give him a standing ovation when he would come in.
And then, too, when I first became director, I followed the procedure, and we would have a prof go through the cabins to help them.
But Haskell, that was creating more distraction.
So I changed it over to a professor in one of the rooms up in the academic building.
administration building.
And that's the way we handled that.
But they did not have to study.
I wouldn't want to get into this core business world.
But they had to be quiet.
And they couldn't be out running around in the other areas.
We had no problem with that.
And many of the better students would go up to almost every health station.
They were going to get everything out of it they could.
And the physical education people were very good.
I had people like Palmer, Les Palmer, Herman Segrist, Paul Andrews.
You know, Paul lived till he was almost 100.
They were good people.
And they fit into the community well.
You know, I had an English prof that was, what was his name?
He was the voice of the Aggies.
Had this Boston accent.
Well,
It will come to us, but I remember, you know this fella could hardly talk without profanity.
And that worried me, because we were going to a small community.
And the A&M Mother's Club,
invited him to speak to them on one of the plays.
And I thought, oh man, this is one I'm going to have to play.
But you know, I worried all afternoon while that was held.
And then the president called me and she said, he's wonderful.
I said,
She said, yes, we've never had a more charming, courteous person.
And I thought, thank God.
And then I thought, you know, he's smart enough.
But it was really, it was a great, it was one of the most pleasant things I've ever done.
It needs to go about 10 seconds.
This is now Monday, May 10, and we're resuming the interview.
And Austin Curley has been trying to summarize in his thoughts the A&M method, the A&M philosophy, the A&M technique of relating to students.
Please go ahead.
Well, the important characteristic of Texas A&M College and University has always been that peculiar but effective relationship between professors and students.
From the beginning, the academic element of the university
was the deciding factor in what direction that the college would go.
In its early days, all the way through, Dean Dean, a distinguished professor that's on our campus, thinks that is the most remarkable thing in the world
about the relationship of students with their profs.
Now, did you encounter that as a student?
Oh, yes.
Oh, yes.
Reflect and reminisce on some examples.
Well, one of the professors that had a great impact on me was Count Segar.
Count Segar was a short man, stocky, short arms, which he waved vigorously when he was trying to make a point.
And he was indeed of royal birth.
He came out of the central Europe, the area where there's so much turmoil now, and apparently his noble family had to leave.
How in the world he got from the East Coast and the Ivy Colleges down to Texas A&M, I was too modest to ask him.
But he was beloved by students.
He enjoyed students.
He took interest in them.
He was not immune from
cutting up with the students sometimes.
I remember one time we were having class and this student was taking issue with him over something.
And he said, Count, it's right here in this book.
And the Count said, where did you get that book?
Oh, he says, so and so.
He said, throw the book out the window.
Well, the old boy did.
Out she went.
Well, everyone looked startled, including the Count, and then we all had a big laugh.
At the end of a course, Count Sigard would have you write a summary of your reaction to the task.
You're free to write anything that you want to.
Then he would take them up and he would read them aloud to the class.
It was no threat to him.
One fellow said, this is the biggest bunch of bullshit I've ever heard.
Count looked up and said, you know, that may be true.
And of course everyone laughed.
But he, but on the other hand though, you could go to him with a serious problem and Council Guard was very, very gracious.
Other examples?
Other people?
Well, I was very fortunate in the fall of 1938, my senior year, to get into the class of a Dr. Geddes.
who was the first distinguished professor on our campus.
And he had come down from the east.
And he was indeed a remarkable man.
Tall fellow.
Family history of his family in Texas for a long time.
And it was just remarkable.
to sit there and listen to someone with the background that he had.
When I looked at the schedule of classes for the spring semester of my senior year, he was teaching two courses.
I signed up for both of them.
One was oil and gas lease laws.
That didn't bother me.
I didn't know what I'd do with it, but I would get to hear him.
And I talked to him.
I visited with him a lot.
Well, we all had.
We liked our professors.
We didn't hesitate to attach names to them.
Dr. Gammon was noted as Oster Joe.
And that was not meant in disrespect, but it was related to his mannerism of clearing his throat.
And that was so remarkable that Dean Dean is trying to write a book about this.

Now, Haskell, I think he needs to think through that very carefully, because you see, when we talk about something that happened 50 years ago, we have to ask ourselves that this is a propitious time for that to come about.
But in all of the history of Texas A&M College and University, there has been this tight bond
And most of the years that I can attest to, the professor had a sincere interest in the students.
Now when you were an undergraduate,
There were still lots of faculty living on campus.
Oh, yes, yes.
Where the Memorial Student Center is now was two rows of homes that swept around to the playground.
Then also back up around Walton Hall, there was a large group.
There are people who grew up on the campus in those halls.
I remember when we got up here in 59, there were still a few of the houses standing where the coldest parking garage is now.
An English faculty member, Dick, he bought one of the last ones and moved it down to South Edge College Station.
I don't think anyone was living in them in 59, but still two or three of the houses were still there.
Did that encourage closer faculty-student relations?
Yes, it did.
I remember the dean of the College of Medicine, Veterinary Medicine, he would work late and he would come across the campus, the Veterinary Medicine building was right
past the old academic building, and Dean Francis.
Dean Francis, small man, but he would walk right by Hart Hall, go right across the street, and invariably we would be marching to the evening meal.
Dean Francis made no point, and there would be frantic halts
We let the dean by, and then we would go on.
It was a great thing.
I think that even the ROTC officers caught this spirit of thing.
Well, it was good.
This same spirit I saw in 1952 when I came back.
These professors were interested in their students.
They would volunteer to serve as faculty advisors.
They would work to go over the test scores with them, help them with schedules, and all that sort of thing.
And it was...

To me, it was such a wonderful thing that in all of the contributions I could make to bring some current organization to really things that had taken place that we were able to do that we couldn't have before World War II.

was well I don't know how it is now I'm not you know qualified but the it could be that among other things at school that it is this spirit and understanding and feeling that makes our student body like it is what are the let's let's
Try to think philosophical.
What are the events?
